{{Chembox <!-- Images --> | ImageFile = Trimethylsulfonium.svg | ImageSize = 120px | ImageAlt = <!-- Names --> | IUPACName = | OtherNames = Trimesium <!-- Sections --> | Section1 = {{Chembox Identifiers | CASNo = 676-84-6 | PubChem = | ChemSpiderID = 1115 | SMILES = C[S+](C)C }} | Section2 = {{Chembox Properties | Formula = C<sub>3</sub>H<sub>9</sub>S<sup>+</sup> | MolarMass = 77.17 g/mol | Appearance = | Density = | MeltingPt = | BoilingPt = | Solubility = }} | Section3 = {{Chembox Hazards | MainHazards = | FlashPt = | AutoignitionPt = }} }}
'''Trimethylsulfonium''' (systematically named '''trimethylsulfanium''' and '''trimethylsulfur(1+)''') is an [[organic chemistry|organic]] [[cation]] with the [[chemical formula]] (CH<sub>3</sub>)<sub>3</sub>S<sup>+</sup> (also written as {{Chem|C|3|H|9|S|+}}). It is the simplest [[sulfonium]] cation.
==Compounds== Several [[salt (chemistry)|salts]] of trimethylsulfonium are known:
