{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}} {{Use Australian English|date=January 2015}} {{Infobox power station |name = Wonthaggi Wind Farm |image = [[File:Wonthaggi wind farm.jpg|frameless|Wonthaggi wind farm]] |location_map = Australia |country = Australia |location = [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] | coordinates = {{coord|38|36|11|S|145|32|26|E|region:AU_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} |owner = [[Origin Energy]] |status = O |commissioned = December 2005 | ps_units_operational= 6 | ps_units_manu_model = REpower: MM82 | wind_hub_height = 66m | wind_rotor_diameter = 82m | wind_rated_speed = 25m/s <ref>{{cite web|title=Technical data about Repower MM82 wind turbine|url=http://www.thewindpower.net/turbine_technical_en_16_repower_mm82.php|accessdate=19 January 2015}}</ref> | wind_farm_type = | wind_site_elevation = | wind_site_usage = | wind_site_area = | wind_offshore_depth = | wind_offshore_distance= | ps_electrical_capacity= 12 MW | ps_electrical_cap_fac= | website = }}
'''Wonthaggi wind farm''' is a [[wind power]] station at [[Wonthaggi, Victoria|Wonthaggi]] in [[Gippsland]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[Australia]]. It has six [[wind turbines]], with a total generating capacity of 12 [[Megawatt|MW]] of [[electricity]].
==Technical Details== Each of the turbines is a German made [[REpower Systems|REpower]] MM82 turbines, each sitting on an Australian made 66m tall tower.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.keppelprince.com/default.asp?id=1,8,0,36 |title=Keppel Prince - REpower: Wonthaggi Wind Farm |accessdate=19 January 2015}}</ref> The farm is operated by [[Origin Energy]] Australia, and became operational in December 2005.
==Blade Snapping Incident== In March 2012 one of the rotor blades snapped,<ref>{{cite news|title=Worries at Victorian wind farm after rotor blade snaps|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/worries-at-victorian-wind-farm-after-rotor-blade-snaps/story-e6frg6nf-1226308666686|accessdate=19 January 2015|newspaper=The Australian|date=24 March 2012}}</ref> [[Senvion]] (formerly [[REpower Systems|REpower]]), the manufacturers of the turbine, replaced the blades and blamed the issue on a manufacturing fault. <ref>{{cite web|title=Senvion - Wonthaggi Blade Incident |url=http://www.senvion.com/au/press-releases/actualite0/datum/2012/07/31/wonthaggi-blade-incident/|accessdate=19 January 2015|date=31 July 2012}}</ref>
